[
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(3) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "When Israel had sown.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—The invasions of these Arab tribes were of the most crushing and irritating kind. Living in idleness and marauding expeditions, they let the Israelites sow their corn, and came themselves to reap and carry it away. They said, “Let us take to ourselves the pastures of God”—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "i.e., ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "the rich, blessed pastures—“in possession” (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 83:12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). Alyattes, king of Lydia, treated the people of Miletus in exactly the same way, leaving their houses un-destroyed, solely that they might be tempted to return to them, and plough and sow once more (Herod. i. 17). The same thing goes on to this day. The wretched Fellahîn, neglected and oppressed by the effete and corrupt Turkish Government, sow their corn, with the constant dread that they are but sowing it for the Bedouin, who yearly plunder them, unrepressed and unpunished. Hence the squalid towns and villages of the Fellahîn abound in huge subterranean places of concealment, in which they stow away their corn, and everything else of value which they possess, to save them from these wild marauders.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The Amalekites.—See Judges 3:13; Genesis 36:12.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "The Amalekites.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—See ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Judges 3:13",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "; ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Genesis 36:12",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ".",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The children of the east.—Benî Kedem (Genesis 25:6; Job 1:3) is a general name for Arabs, as Josephus rightly calls them. From Judges 8:26 we can derive a picture of their chiefs in their gorgeous robes and golden ear-rings, mounted on dromedaries and camels, of which the necks were hung with moon-shaped ornaments of gold.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "The children of the east.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—Benî Kedem (",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Genesis 25:6",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "; ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Job 1:3",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ") is a general name for Arabs, as Josephus rightly calls them. From ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Judges 8:26",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " we can derive a picture of their chiefs in their gorgeous robes and golden ear-rings, mounted on dromedaries and camels, of which the necks were hung with moon-shaped ornaments of gold.",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Benson Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Jdg 6:3-5",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Jdg 6:3-5",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "The children of the east — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Probably the Ishmaelites, or Arabians, especially the eastern part of them. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Unto Gaza — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "That is, from the east, on which side they entered, to the west, where Gaza was, near the Mediterranean sea. So that they destroyed the whole land. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Without number — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "That is, so many that it was not easy to number them. And not in a regular army to engage, but in a confused swarm, to plunder the country. Yet Israel, being forsaken of God, had not spirit to make head against them; God fighting against them with those very terrors with which otherwise he would have fought for them. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Matthew Henry's Concise Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "6:1-6 Israel's sin was renewed, and Israel's troubles were repeated. Let all that sin expect to suffer. The Israelites hid themselves in dens and caves; such was the effect of a guilty conscience. Sin dispirits men. The invaders left no food for Israel, except what was taken into the caves. They prepared that for Baal with which God should have been served, now God justly sends an enemy to take it away in the season thereof.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Barnes' Notes on the Bible",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The word rendered \"dens\" is only found in this passage. It is best explained of ravines hollowed out by torrents, which the Israelites made into hiding-places. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
